 Then later add an ANN index appropriate for your setup. pgvector supports exact and approximate nearest-neighbor search and multiple distance strategies such as cosine, inner product, and L2Then later add an ANN index appropriate for your setup. pgvector supports exact and approximate nearest-neighbor search and multiple distance strategies such as cosine, inner product, and L2

 1. Hybrid Search (The "SQL + Vector" Power)
 Since you are using PGVector, you have a massive advantage: Full-Text Search (TSVector).
 The Workflow: When you ingest a PDF, don't just store the embedding.
 Store the raw text in a TSVECTOR column in Postgres.

 The Logic: When a user asks a question, perform a "Hybrid Search" that combines the BM25 (keyword) score with
  the Vector (semantic) score.
 Why: If a user searches for a specific part number like "X-5090," vector search might fail, but keyword search will nail it. Combining them makes your bot "smart."


 2. Re-ranking (The "Precision" Layer)
 This is where your RTX 5090 shines.
 The Workflow:
 Retrieve the top 20 chunks from PGVector.
 Send those 20 chunks + the user query to a local Cross-Encoder model (like cross-encoder/ms-marco-MiniLM-L-6-v2) running on your GPU.
 The Re-ranker gives each chunk a new "relevance score."
 Send only the top 5 re-ranked chunks to your LLM.
 Why: This significantly reduces "hallucinations" because the LLM only sees the absolute most relevant data.


 3. Observability (The "Management" Layer)
 Integrate LangSmith (it has a free tier) into your Spring Boot app.
 The Visual: Your dashboard will show: "Input Query" -> "Postgres Retrieval (20ms)" -> "Re-ranker (50ms)" -> "LLM Generation (500ms)."
 The Flex: In an interview, you can open your laptop and show them the trace. Seeing the logic flow visually makes you 10x more memorable than other candidates.

 What to do next in Java:
 Dependency: Add langchain4j-open-ai (for LangSmith tracking) and langchain4j-local-ai (to run your Re-ranker locally).
 SQL: Update your Postgres table to include a metadata JSONB column and a text_search_vector column.
 Prompt: Update your LLM prompt to say: "Using the following RE-RANKED context, answer the user's question..."


Step 1

👉 Answer evaluation (LLM judge)
Implemented a dual-model AI pipeline using a local LLM for answer generation and OpenAI for answer evaluation.
Added LLM-as-judge scoring for groundedness, correctness, and completeness to measure response quality and support future fallback logic.

Designed and implemented a production-style AI pipeline with:
- Hybrid retrieval (BM25 + vector + RRF fusion)
- Cross-encoder style reranking
- Dynamic query routing (RAG vs Agent)
- LLM-as-judge evaluation using OpenAI to score groundedness, correctness, and completeness
- Fault-tolerant evaluation layer with retries and graceful degradation
 - We decoupled evaluation from user-facing latency by running LLM-as-judge asynchronously, allowing us to collect quality metrics without impacting response time.

